st"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"maritime","header":"He anchored to a spar and lived","body":"In a Biscay hurricane in January 1814, with his schooner’s planksheer split open to the hold, Coggeshall rigged a square-sail boom on sixty fathoms of cable and rode to it head-to-wind — “like a gull on the water.” Five British transports wrecked in the same gale; the David Porter sailed into Lateste six days later."},{"number":2,"category":"maritime","header":"A cargo that fought its way over","body":"A letter-of-marque was not quite a privateer: armed and commissioned, but carrying cargo to a destination — “force trade and fight their way or run.” He outran the brig Dotterall to Charleston bar, traded salt for cotton, and beat Wellington’s army to Bordeaux by weeks."},{"number":3,"category":"literature","header":"He wrote it all down at seventy","body":"Thirty years after the war the old captain assembled his logbooks and memories into book form — sixty years at sea, told with a lively pen. American Heritage was still printing his adventures in 1957."}],"slug":"george-coggeshall-1784"},"HD6322":{"id":"HD6322","bio":{"display_name":"Robert Coggeshall","gender":"male"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":false,"number_of_marriages":0,"tags":["lost_at_sea"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1788,"month":6,"day":29},"death":{"year":1810},"marriages":[],"parents":{"father_id":"X03291","mother_id":"HD6319"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005"},"slug":"robert-coggeshall-hd6322"},"HD6323":{"id":"HD6323","bio":{"display_name":"Ann Coggeshall","gender":"female"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_d